-- Crude Options Volatility Slips From Four-Week High as Oil Rises
-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 2013-05-30T20:17:43Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-05-30/crude-options-volatility-slips-from-four-week-high-as-oil-rises.html
Crude oil options volatility slipped
from a four-week high as the underlying futures advanced.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
July, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 21.99 percent at 3:25 p.m. on the New
York Mercantile Exchange, down from 22.95 percent yesterday.  West Texas Intermediate crude for July delivery rose 48
cents to $93.61 a barrel on the Nymex after falling yesterday to
the lowest settlement since May 1.  The most-active options in electronic trading today were
July $90 puts, which fell 24 cents to 65 cents a barrel on
volume of 10,754 contracts at 3:32 p.m. in New York. September
$85 puts were the second-most active, declining 9 cents to $1.30
on 5,091 lots.  Puts accounted for 63 percent of electronic trading volume
today and 54 percent of the prior trading dayâ€™s volume of
106,146 contracts.  July $90 puts were the most-active options traded in the
previous session, with 6,214 contracts changing hands. They rose
38 cents to 89 cents a barrel. July $95 calls fell 81 cents to
$1.08 a barrel on 6,098 lots.  Open interest was highest for December $105 calls with
38,050 contracts. Next were July $110 calls with 35,794 lots and
July $90 puts with 34,909.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
